3. Free Use

You may exercise the rights granted in Section 2 as Free Use if:

1. you are an individual acting on your own behalf;
2. you are a Nonprofit Organization;
3. you are an Educational Institution; or
4. you are an Organization that has not exceeded the Enterprise Threshold.

Free Use includes internal development, testing, staging, production use,
self-hosting, and internal modifications, subject to this License.

4. Trial Use After the Enterprise Threshold

If an Organization first exceeds the Enterprise Threshold, that Organization
receives a one-time Trial Period of ninety (90) days.

During the Trial Period, the Organization may continue to use, self-host, test,
evaluate, and internally deploy the Licensed Work, subject to this License.

When the Trial Period ends, continued use by that Organization requires a
Commercial License unless and until the Organization no longer exceeds the
Enterprise Threshold. The Trial Period does not reset if the Organization later
drops below the Enterprise Threshold and then exceeds it again.

5. Uses That Require a Commercial License

Without a Commercial License, you may not:

1. continue using the Licensed Work after the Trial Period if your Organization
   exceeds the Enterprise Threshold;
2. use the Licensed Work to operate, offer, or enable a Hosted Service that is
   a Competing Offering;
3. embed, white-label, OEM, sublicense, or otherwise provide the Licensed Work
   as a material part of a Competing Offering;
4. represent that your fork, service, or product is endorsed by or affiliated
   with Nimbus or the Licensor;
5. obtain rights reserved by Section 10 on trademarks and branding.

For clarity, using the Licensed Work to power your own application, website, or
internal system is allowed if your use otherwise complies with this License. The
restriction in this Section applies to offering Nimbus itself, or a materially
similar managed backend/database/platform service, to third parties.

